{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17503570","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17503570"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T11:03:25+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T11:03:25+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2046"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2046","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2046"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.46,0.15,0.23,0.05,0.11]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2046"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"92377"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2046","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2046"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2046"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"75682"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"3975"},{"type":"tags","id":"4578"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"31534"},{"type":"contributions","id":"31535"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"92377","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/92377"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 40-year-old woman is being discharged from hospital after a severe episode of biliary colic, in which she reported severe right upper quadrant pain. This was managed non-operatively and she was given PRN subcutaneous fentanyl for analgesia and improved clinically over 24 hours. She is otherwise well and has no known allergies.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which of the following is the most appropriate discharge medication for pain relief as required?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Paracetamol/codeine 500/30mg oral tablet","Tramadol 50mg slow release oral tablet","Tramadol 50mg immediate release oral tablet","Fentanyl patch 100 mcg/h for 72 hours","Oxycodone 15 mg slow release oral tablet"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETramadol 50mg immediate release oral tablet\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate choice for analgesia in these circumstances. Codeine has a spasmodic effect on the sphincter of Oddi, and so should be avoided in biliary colic. It was even associated with acute pancreatitis in patients with history of cholecystectomy (odds ratio 2.64) in a large case controlled study. \u003Cbr /\u003E\u003Cbr /\u003ESlow release opioids and patches are inappropriate for the treatment of acute pain. A 2018 position statement from the Australian and New Zealand College of Anaesthetists: \u2018the inappropriate use of slow-release opioids for the treatment of acute pain has been associated with a significant risk of respiratory depression, resulting in severe adverse events and deaths.\u2019\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Tramadol provides effective pain relief for recently treated biliary colic."],"references":["Afghani E, Lo SK, Covington PS, Cash BD, Pandol SJ. Sphincter of Oddi Function and Risk Factors for Dysfunction. Front Nutr. 2017 Jan 30;4:1.","Kim J, Tabner A, Johnson G, Brumback B, Hartzema A. Increased Risk of Acute Pancreatitis with Codeine Use in Patients with a History of Cholecystectomy. Digestive Diseases and Sciences. 2020 Jan1; 65(1): 292\u2013300.","Hattingh K, Macintyre P, Schug S, Craigie M, Hore P. Statement on the Use of Slow-Release Opioid Preparations in the Treatment of Acute Pain. ANZCA Bulletin 2018 March."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"75682"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2046"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanatio